trans-unit.note:
I don't think "suojausavain" is the correct word to use for translating "passkey".
That's what the physical security devices like YubiKeys and Titan Security Keys are called. All the big companies like Google, Microsoft and Apple use that word for them.
Better words for "passkey" would be "avainkoodi", which is what Google calls them, or "todentamisavain", which is the word Microsoft, Apple and others use.

@finl Well Google does not live in Finland and maybe we shouldn't mimic from them if we don't want to give future of our language to the hands of outsiders. Or we will have problems like "tammikuutata, helmikuutata ..." again. :D
In any case in ICT I do use many of those words and also avainkoodi when talking to the laymen (like locker or phone PIN-number) and in more professionally usually use words that have more descriptive meaning. Because it's not really PIN-number that we meant here. Maybe you had in mind hardware tokens as those perform the same function, but in our case it's text that we use to confirm our "rights of access". All those words are good as long as the target audience understands what to do with the given information as intuitively as possible.
I have never used "todentamisavain" my self when writing, as I associate it to completely different context, more to the confirmation of something.
I think it's a bit about familiarity of words, I think that in this case the "Suojaus...avain" still leads people to quite good thought context, maybe more than "Avain...koodi" can.

@amarkula
The point wasn't whether this translation makes logical sense or fits the meaning of the word or not, but simply about the fact that "suojausavain" is already in popular use as the word used for the physical security key devices.
I'm thinking about what the user will if they look these words up, because that is what people do when they don't know what something means.
If you search for "suojausavain", all the results will be support pages for Google, Microsoft, Apple, Facebook, etc, explaining what security keys are and how to use them.
So it just doesn't seem like a good idea to me to use the same existing word.

@amarkula I have now changed all "passkey" strings to translate as "p√§√§syavain". This is the term that Apple uses (no, I'm not an Apple fan, I just think that it's the most on point option, at least at this time :).
I also changed all "security key" strings to use "suojausavain" as @finl had suggested because it true that it seems to be the most used translation. Back when I originally locked these to "todennuslaite", passkeys weren't really a thing yet and even security keys were still pretty new (or to be more accurate, not nearly as widely supported as they are now), and I wanted to emphasize the hardware side a bit more.
Now, like within the last a year or two, both of these have spread far and wide but even the source terminology is still kind of a mess depending on platform, device manufacturers, service providers etc. We will have to see where it goes and try to adjust these accordingly.
If you see any strings that I may have overlooked or otherwise f'd up, point them out and I'll fix them!
